To start version control of a directory(or to create a local Git repo), initiate it into Git using the command :
git init (creates a local git repo)
(a hidden file .git/ is created in the directory, use "ls -a" to print the same)

git status (to check status of the directory)
git add file_name (moves the file to the staging area)
git rm --cached file_name (to untrack the file)
git commit -m "added file_name" (to commit changes made to the file)
git rm file_name (the file is deleted from the local repo)
git restore file_name (file is restored from remote rep to the local)
git add . (moves all file at once to the staging area)
git log (tracks changes/ who made what changes & when)
git log --online (all logs in one line, where the HEAD points to the latest commit)
git branch (shows different branches)
git checkout -b dev (creates a* switches to a new branch "dev")
git checkout master/git switch dev (switches to the branch of our choice)
git merge dev (merges one branch into another, first switch to the main branch & run the merge command)
git remote -v (checks if the local repo is connected to any remote repo)
git remote add origin https://github.com/NavinHajari/file_name (to establish connection with a remote repo, where "origin" is a variable to hold the github link)
git remote set-url origin personal-token-collected-from-github@https://github.com/NavinHajari/file_name
git push origin master (to push changes to the remote repo after establishing connection with it)
git pull origin master (to pull changes from the remote repo to the local)
git diff (shows difference)
git fetch (fetches all the branches)

Accessing a repo on Github using SSH:
1. Generate a key pair
 ssh-keygen
2. Get the public key & paste it on Github
3. Go to the global settings --> SSH & GPG keys --> Click "Add new ssh key" & paste the key & click add
4. Now get the ssh link of the repo to copy from the Github
5. Git clone git@github.com/NavinHajari/90DaysDevOps

